Introduction

This data set provides the health conditions of both smokers and non smokers. The discription of the data set is as follows.
Age: Age of a representative in years
Sex: Gender of a representative (male, female)
current_smoker: Whether the representative is smoking or not (yes, no)
heart_rate: Heart rate of a representative
blood_pressure: Heart rate of a representative (systolic blood pressure/diastolic blood pressure)
cigs_per_day: Number of cigarettes consumed per day
chol: cholesterol level of a representative

Discussion

  1. In the original data set both systolic and diastolic blood pressures were indicated together as blood pressure. But for the convenience of analysis it was separated as two quantitative variables.
  2. All the outliers indicated by the box plot are not removed because some of can be happened in real scenarios. But some outliers are eliminated because they indicate as extreme outliers and show less number of outliers separately.
  3. Removed outliers are taken as null values.
  4. Missing values of categorical variables are also assigned as null values.
  5. Since the data points are not scattered perfectly, a smooth line is used to detect the trend.
  6. The data may contain variability due to measurement error, unmeasured confounding variables, or differences in participant health status.

Conclusions

  1. Number of females are higher than number of males but number of smoking males are higher than number of smoking females.
  2. The average cholesterol level in the data set is around 236 mg/dL, which is relatively high compared to the commonly recommended healthy range.
  3. Average heart rate does not significantly vary with respect to the smoking condition.
  4. The magnitude of correlation coefficients are not close to one and that means there are no strong relationships among quantitative variables except the relationship between systolic blood pressure and diastolic blood pressure.
  5. Systolic blood pressure and diastolic blood pressure are declined when the daily cigarette consumption is increasing.
  6. Heart rate and cholesterol level is increasing when the daily cigarette consumption is increasing.
  7. Heart rate is increased when Systolic blood pressure and diastolic blood pressure are increased.
